\begin_layout Standard

The approach to statistical Multi-step Direct
\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

MSD
\end_layout

\end_inset

 reactions is based on the Multi-step Direct (MSD) theory of preequilibrium scattering to the continuum originally proposed by Tamura, Udagawa and Lenske 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after ""
key "TUL"

\end_inset

. Since then, the approach has been revised, especially the part related to statistical and dynamical treatment of nuclear structure.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

The evolution of the projectile-target system from small to large energy losses in the open channel space is described in the MSD theory with a combination of direct reaction (DR), microscopic nuclear structure and statistical methods. As typical for the DR-approach, it is assumed that the closed channel space, i.e. the MSC
\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

MSC
\end_layout

\end_inset

 contributions, have been projected out and can be treated separately within the Multi-step Compound
\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

MSC
\end_layout

\end_inset

 mechanism.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec: MSD"

\end_inset

Outline of the theory
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

In the MSD
\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

MSD
\end_layout

\end_inset

 theory the effective Hamiltonian in the open channel space is divided into an energy averaged optical model part 
\begin_inset Formula $H^{opt}$
\end_inset

, describing the relative motion of projectile 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and target 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, the intrinsic Hamiltonian 
\begin_inset Formula $H^{intr}$
\end_inset

 of the asymptotically separated nuclei and the residual effective projectile-target interaction 
\begin_inset Formula $V^{res}$
\end_inset

 leading to non-elastic processes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
H=H^{opt}+H^{intr}+V^{res}\quad.\label{fullh}\end{equation}
\end_inset

 Both 
\begin_inset Formula $H^{opt}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $V^{res}$
\end_inset

 are non-hermitian operators. To a large extent the imaginary parts are related to the flux absorbed into the closed channels, but those open channels which are not treated explicitly are also contributing.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

The ORION
\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

ORION
\end_layout

\end_inset

 code solves the Lippmann-Schwinger equation for the open channel T-matrix where the 
\begin_inset Formula $n^{th}$
\end_inset

-order term
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
T_{\gamma0}^{(n)}=<\chi_{E}^{(-)}|(\gamma|V^{res}(G^{chan}(E)V^{res})^{n-1}|0)|\chi_{0}^{(+)}>\label{tgamman}\end{equation}
\end_inset

 describes the 
\begin_inset Formula $n-$
\end_inset

step transition from the entrance channel with incoming scattering wave 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi_{0}^{(+)}$
\end_inset

 and the ground state configuration 
\begin_inset Formula $|0)=|aA)$
\end_inset

 to an exit channel 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 with outgoing wave 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi_{E}^{(-)}$
\end_inset

 at the energy E 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after ""
key "SLW,LW92"

\end_inset

. 
\begin_inset Formula $G^{chan}(E)$
\end_inset

 is the Green's function for the channel. The scattering waves are optical model wave functions. They are weakly energy dependent on a scale much larger than the one on which the intrinsic states 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 vary. The MSD
\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

MSD
\end_layout

\end_inset

 approach treats the residual projectile-target interactions perturbatively. In this sense, MSD theory is a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

weak coupling
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 description of continuum scattering.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

In order to describe the statistical content of pre-equilibrium spectra the real states 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 are expanded into 
\emph on
n
\emph default
-particle and 
\emph on
n
\emph default
-hole model states 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

. Explicitly, 
\begin_inset Formula $H^{intr}$
\end_inset

 is chosen as 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
H^{intr}=H_{0}^{intr}+V^{intr}\quad.\label{hintr}\end{equation}
\end_inset

 The states 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 are eigenstates of 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{0}^{intr}$
\end_inset

 and the residual interaction 
\begin_inset Formula $V^{intr}$
\end_inset

 couples states from different particle-hole classes only. It is assumed that the configuration mixing between 
\begin_inset Formula $np-nh$
\end_inset

 classes is stochastic in nature and leads to a random distribution of amplitudes with mean value zero 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after ""
key "LW92"

\end_inset

. When the density matrix is averaged over a finite energy interval, e.g. with a Lorentzian or Gaussian 
\begin_inset Formula $g(x)$
\end_inset

 of full width 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta$
\end_inset

 large compared to the mean level spacing, 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\hat{\rho}(E)=\int dE'g(E-E')\hat{\rho}_{micro}(E)\label{rhoav}\end{equation}
\end_inset

 the coherence of the basis states is lost. As a result, the density matrix becomes a statistical matrix 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\hat{\rho}(E)=\sum_{n}{\hat{\rho}_{n}(E)}.\label{levelc}\end{equation}
\end_inset

 The summation extends over the 
\begin_inset Formula $np-nh$
\end_inset

 classes with 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\hat{\rho}_{n}(E)=\sum_{c=[npnh]}{|c)P_{c}(E)(c|}\label{leveld}\end{equation}
\end_inset

 and the probability per energy to find the system in the configuration 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 is given by the spectroscopic densities,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
P_{c}(E)=-\frac{1}{\pi}Im[\int dE'g(E-E')(c|G^{intr}(E')|c)]\,,\label{specd}\end{equation}
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $G^{intr}(E)$
\end_inset

 being the intrinsic Green's function.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

The statistical operators carry further properties which are important for the physical content of the description. Integrating 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{c}(E)$
\end_inset

 over an interval 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta E$
\end_inset

 one obtains the spectroscopic factor for the configuration 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta E$
\end_inset

. Irrespective of the representation, i.e. in either the 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 or the 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 basis, the trace of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\rho}(E)$
\end_inset

, Eq. 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "rhoav"

\end_inset

, gives the total level density
\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

level density
\end_layout

\end_inset

 at energy 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

. The partial level density of 
\begin_inset Formula $np-nh$
\end_inset

 states is determined by 
\begin_inset Formula $tr(\hat{\rho}_{n})$
\end_inset

 (Eq. 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "leveld"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

Similar to the chaining and never-come-back hypotheses of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after ""
key "FKK"

\end_inset

 the interference terms 
\begin_inset Formula $n\ne k$
\end_inset

 are neglected by assuming that in each step the reaction is dominated by transitions into configurations with the highest level density at a given excitation energy. This means, that we neglect de-excitation and re-scattering processes which decrease or leave the 
\begin_inset Formula $ph-$
\end_inset

number unchanged, respectively. With this assumption the cross section becomes an incoherent super-position of 
\begin_inset Formula $n-$
\end_inset

step contributions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\frac{d^{2}\sigma}{d\Omega dE}=\sum_{n}{\frac{d^{2}\sigma^{(n)}}{d\Omega dE}}\,,\label{sigma0}\end{equation}
\end_inset

 where the multi-step cross sections are defined as 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\frac{d^{2}\sigma^{(n)}}{d\Omega dE}=\sum_{c=[npnh]}{P_{c}(E)|T_{c0}^{(n)}|^{2}}\,.\label{sign}\end{equation}
\end_inset

 Expanding 
\begin_inset Formula $V^{res}$
\end_inset

 into multi-poles 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 and noting that only 
\begin_inset Formula $1p-1h$
\end_inset

 configurations are directly excited in a one-step process the 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma^{(1)}$
\end_inset

 is determined by an average over transitions into the 
\begin_inset Formula $1p-1h$
\end_inset

 states 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 around excitation energy 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 with form factors 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
F_{\lambda}^{c0}=(c|V_{\lambda}|0)\,.\end{equation}
\end_inset

 Rather than treating each transition separately it is sufficient to consider averages over the microscopic form factors. Thus, 
\begin_inset Formula $V^{res}$
\end_inset

 is represented in terms of state independent multipole form factors 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 and nuclear transition operators 
\begin_inset Formula $O_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
V^{res}(r,\xi)=\sum_{\lambda}{F_{\lambda}(r)O_{\lambda}(\xi)}.\label{vres}\end{equation}
\end_inset

 Here, 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 denotes the relative motion coordinate and 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi=(\xi_{a},\xi_{A})$
\end_inset

 are the intrinsic coordinates including spin and isospin, respectively. The multipole form factors 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 in turn are related to 
\begin_inset Formula $O_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

. In a self-consistent approach they are obtained by averaging 
\begin_inset Formula $V^{res}$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $O_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
F_{\lambda}(r)=(c|O_{\lambda}^{\dag}\hat{\rho}(E)V^{res}|c)/S_{\lambda}(E,c).\label{formf}\end{equation}
\end_inset

 Here, the general case of a transition starting from an arbitrary state 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 is considered which appears in the intermediate steps of higher order multi-step processes. For one-step reactions the initial state is the ground state 
\begin_inset Formula $c=0$
\end_inset

. By normalization to the transition strength function 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{\lambda}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
(c|O_{\lambda'}^{\dag}\hat{\rho}(E)O_{\lambda}|c)=\delta_{\lambda\lambda'}S_{\lambda}(E,c)\label{slambda}\end{equation}
\end_inset

 the dependence of the form factor on the internal state is removed to a large extent. 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 is the nuclear response function for the external operator 
\begin_inset Formula $O_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 describing the transition rate per unit energy from the state 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 into the ensemble of states 
\begin_inset Formula $c'$
\end_inset

 centered at energy 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

The above relations are appropriate for one-step reactions where 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 is the ground state. However, in higher steps 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 is an arbitrary intermediate 
\begin_inset Formula $np-nh$
\end_inset

 state which is summed over in the cross section. Thus, for multi-step scattering the form factor, Eq.
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "formf"

\end_inset

 actually utilizes a too microscopic picture. The statistical aspects in multi-step transitions are taken fully into account by the average multipole form factors 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
F_{\lambda}=\frac{tr(\hat{\rho}O_{\lambda}^{\dag}\hat{\rho}V^{res})}{tr(\hat{\rho}O_{\lambda}^{\dag}\hat{\rho}O_{\lambda})}\,,\label{fav}\end{equation}
\end_inset

 which are independent of the initial state and the multi-step order, respectively. In the applications of the theory these global form factors together with the response functions of Eq.
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "slambda"

\end_inset

 are used.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

With the above results the one-step cross section is expressed as 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\frac{d^{2}\sigma^{(1)}}{dEd\Omega}=\sum_{\lambda}{S_{\lambda}(E)\overline{\frac{d\sigma^{(1)}}{d\Omega}}\mid_{\lambda}}\,,\label{sigma1}\end{equation}
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\sigma^{(1)}}$
\end_inset

 is a reduced DWBA
\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

DWBA
\end_layout

\end_inset

 cross section calculated with the average form factors (Eq.
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "formf"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

The multi-step part of the theory is discussed here for two-step reactions only. The state-independent and slowly varying two-step amplitudes read
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
T_{\lambda_{1},\lambda_{2}}^{(2)}=<\chi_{E}^{(-)}|F_{\lambda_{2}}G^{opt}F_{\lambda_{1}}|\chi_{\alpha}^{(+)}>\,,\label{amp2}\end{equation}
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $G^{opt}$
\end_inset

 being Green's function for the optical model potential. The nuclear structure information is now contained completely in 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
(0|O_{\lambda'_{1}}^{\dag}G^{(intr)\dag}(E'_{1})O_{\lambda'_{2}}^{\dag}\hat{\rho}(E)O_{\lambda_{2}}G^{(intr)}(E_{1})O_{\lambda_{1}}|0)\,.\label{two1}\end{equation}
\end_inset

 By definition, the exit channel configurations are 
\begin_inset Formula $2p-2h$
\end_inset

 states which are excited from 
\begin_inset Formula $1p-1h$
\end_inset

 states 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{1}$
\end_inset

. Also in the first step only 
\begin_inset Formula $1p-1h$
\end_inset

 states 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 are excited. Therefore, we only have to consider the 
\begin_inset Formula $1p-1h$
\end_inset

 reduced parts of the two Green functions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

To a good approximation the dependence of 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{\lambda_{2}}(E,c_{1})$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{1}$
\end_inset

 can be replaced by a dependence on 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{1}$
\end_inset

 by considering that the spectroscopic strength usually is located in the vicinity of the unperturbed energy. Theoretically, this is achieved by taking the average over the response functions belonging to states 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{1}$
\end_inset

 at energy 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{1}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray}
S_{\lambda}(E,E_{1}) & = & \frac{\sum_{c_{1}}{P_{c_{1}}(E_{1})S_{\lambda}(E,c_{1})}}{\sum_{c_{1}}{P_{c_{1}}(E_{1})}}\nonumber \\
 & = & \frac{tr(\hat{\rho}_{1}(E_{1})O_{\lambda}^{\dag}\hat{\rho}(E)O_{\lambda})}{tr(\hat{\rho}_{1}(E_{1}))}\quad.\label{slave}\end{eqnarray}
\end_inset

 The final result for the two-step MSD
\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

MSD
\end_layout

\end_inset

 cross section is of very intuitive structure 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
{d^{2}\sigma^{(2)}}/{dEd\Omega}=\sum_{\lambda_{1}\lambda_{2}}{\int dE_{1}S_{\lambda_{2}}(E,E_{1})S_{\lambda_{1}}(E_{1},0)\overline{\frac{d\sigma^{(2)}}{d\Omega}}(E,E_{1})\mid_{\lambda_{1}\lambda_{2}}}.\label{sigma2}\end{equation}
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\sigma^{(2)}}$
\end_inset

 is an averaged cross section defined in terms of the 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{(2)}-$
\end_inset

matrix elements (Eq.
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "amp2"

\end_inset

, which describes two-step scattering wave-mechanically as a coherent quantal process. The total response of the intrinsic system at energy loss 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 is contained in the first and second step transition strength functions. The folding accounts for the partitions of the total energy 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 into one- and two-step parts such that 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 is conserved.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

In the present version of the code only one- and two-step MSD
\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

MSD
\end_layout

\end_inset

 contributions are considered. In most cases it is a good approximation to use the ground state response functions also for the second step but at an energy shifted by the amount of total energy loss in the first step. This corresponds to the assumption that the structure of excited nuclei is close to the structure of the ground state as far as single particle occupancies and other mean-field properties are concerned.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

Summarizing this section, the statistical properties of pre-equilibrium spectra are used to eliminate interference contributions at various places. Physically, this corresponds to the neglect of certain intrinsic correlation functions which only would be observable at an energy resolution of the order of the average level spacing. This leads to a representation of pre-equilibrium cross sections as an incoherent super-position of multi-step contributions. The statistical treatment is introduced in a minimal way, namely referring only to the intrinsic systems while multi-step scattering is described quantum-mechanically as a coherent process at all steps.
\end_layout

