\begin_layout Standard

The emission of 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 in the Multi-step Compound
\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

MSC
\end_layout

\end_inset

 mechanism is treated in terms of the model proposed by Hoering and Weidenmueller 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after ""
key "GammaMSC"

\end_inset

. Application follows the paper by Herman 
\emph on
et al
\emph default
. 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after ""
key "GammaMSCapp"

\end_inset

. The model assumes that 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 emission occurs through the deexcitation of the Giant Dipole Resonance (GDR) built within MSC
\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

MSC
\end_layout

\end_inset

 classes. Following Brink-Axel hypothesis 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after ""
key "Axel,Brink,Brinka"

\end_inset

 each nuclear state serves as the basis of a GDR excitation with identical properties. Moreover, the Tamm-Dancoff approximation is used and GDR is represented as a linear combination of correlated 1p-1h states. Each MSC class 
\emph on
M,
\emph default
 now characterized also by its spin 
\emph on
J,
\emph default
 splits into four sub-classes 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{n}$
\end_inset

. The states in subclasses 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{n}$
\end_inset

, with 
\emph on
n
\emph default
=1, 2 and 3 contain GDR built on states in class 
\emph on
M-1
\emph default
 with spins 
\emph on
J-1, J
\emph default
, and 
\emph on
J+1
\emph default
, respectively, and opposite parity. The states in class 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{4}$
\end_inset

 are pure single particle excitations and contain no GDR.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

The pure MSC-contribution to the cross section is obtained while neglecting the GDR built on the ground state, which leads to the non-statistical direct-semidirect process. The theory 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after ""
key "GammaMSC"

\end_inset

 allows for the inclusion of direct-semidirect in the formalism. However, the implementation of direct-semidirect in the EMPIRE is oversimplified and has been disabled. On the other hand, an option is provided to start MSC
\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

MSC
\end_layout

\end_inset

 calculations right from the first class. This approach lacks formal justification but brings the model closer to the treatment of 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 emission in the classical preequilibrium models.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

The average MSC cross section is given by 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\overline{\sigma_{a,\gamma}^{MSC}}=T_{a,Mm}\Pi_{Mm,Nn}T_{Nn,\gamma},\label{GammaMSCxs}\end{equation}
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray}
(\Pi^{-1})_{Mm,Nn} & = & 2\pi\rho_{Mm}v_{Mm,Nn}2\pi\rho_{Nn}\nonumber \\
 &  & +\delta_{M,N}\delta_{m,n}2\pi\rho_{Mm}(\Gamma_{Mm}^{\uparrow}+\Gamma_{Mm}^{\downarrow})\label{Pigamma}\end{eqnarray}
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{a}=\sum_{Mm}T_{aMm}$
\end_inset

 are the optical model transmission coefficients.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

The transmission coefficients for the 
\emph on
E1
\emph default
-
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 channel are defined, as for the particle channel, in terms of the unitarity deficit of the average 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

-matrix. 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
T_{\gamma}=1-\Big|\overline{S_{\gamma\gamma}}\Big|^{2}.\end{equation}
\end_inset

 This is directly proportional to the strength function 
\begin_inset Formula $f(E)$
\end_inset

, which can be written as a function of the absorption cross section, yielding 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
T_{\gamma}^{E_{1}}=\frac{1}{2\pi}\sigma_{abs}(E_{\gamma}^{E_{1}})\frac{(E_{\gamma}^{E_{1}})^{2}}{(\hbar c)^{2}}.\end{equation}
\end_inset

 The absorption cross section has a Lorentzian form and is given by 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\sigma_{abs}(E_{\gamma}^{E_{1}})=\sigma_{res}\frac{(E_{\gamma}^{E_{1}})^{2}\Gamma_{res}^{2}}{((E_{\gamma}^{E_{1}})^{2}-E_{res}^{2})^{2}+(E_{\gamma}^{E_{1}})^{2}\Gamma_{res}^{2}}.\end{equation}
\end_inset

 For the resonance energy 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{res}$
\end_inset

, the resonance width 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma_{res}$
\end_inset

, and the peak cross section 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{res}$
\end_inset

, the experimental or systematics data are used as input parameters. As in the case of particle emission, the average matrix element 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{Mm,Nn}$
\end_inset

 coupling non-collective states of two exciton classes is determined from the imaginary part of the optical model potential.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

Next, we will analyze the individual matrix elements 
\begin_inset Formula $(\Pi^{-1})_{Mm,Nn}$
\end_inset

. We begin by investigating the non-diagonal block 
\begin_inset Formula $(\Pi^{-1})_{Mm,(M+1)n}=2\pi\rho_{Mm}v_{Mm,(M+1)n}^{2}2\pi\rho_{(M+1)n}$
\end_inset

, i. e., the transition from a state in exciton class 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 to a state in the next higher exciton class 
\begin_inset Formula $(M+1)$
\end_inset

. There are four different types of matrix elements:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

decay of a GDR, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

the single particle transitions leaving the GDR unchanged, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

transitions among non-collective states, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

GDR creation. 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

Computation of these four types of matrix elements is discussed below.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard


\series bold
(i)
\series default
 The matrix element 
\begin_inset Formula $(\Pi^{-1})_{Mm,(M+1)4}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $m=$
\end_inset

 1, 2 or 3 describes the decay of a GDR via coupling to the next higher exciton class. This process is responsible for the spreading width of the GDR. In colliding with a bound particle the GDR looses its coherence and the bound particle is excited into an excited state thus creating another particle-hole state. This matrix element can be written as 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
2\pi\rho_{Mm}v_{Mm,(M+1)4}^{2}2\pi\rho_{(M+1)4}=2\pi\rho_{Mm}\Gamma_{GDR}^{\downarrow}.\end{equation}
\end_inset

 For the width of the GDR the experimental value is used. Unfortunately, there is little literature on how this width is separated into spreading and decay width. It is known that for heavy nuclei the spreading width is dominant, whereas for light nuclei the reverse is true. For 
\begin_inset Formula $^{208}$
\end_inset

Pb approximately 90% of the width is due to the spreading width. For 
\begin_inset Formula $^{16}$
\end_inset

O, on the other hand, 90% of the width is due to the decay width 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after ""
key "BBB83"

\end_inset

. This separation can be entered into the calculations as an input parameter. The result depends only weakly on this coefficient. The level densit
\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

p-h level density
\end_layout

\end_inset

ies 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{Mm}^{J,\pi}(E)$
\end_inset

 for m=1,2,3 are given by the exciton level densities 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{M-1}^{(J-1),-\pi}(E-E_{GDR})$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{M-1}^{J,-\pi}(E-E_{GDR})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{M-1}^{(J+1),-\pi}(E-E_{GDR})$
\end_inset

, respectively. These correspond to the level densities of the non-collective states on which GDR is built. Implicitly, all of them are for bound configurations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard


\series bold
(ii)
\series default
 The matrix element 
\begin_inset Formula $(\Pi^{-1})_{Mm,(M+1)n}$
\end_inset

, m, n=1, 2, 3 describes the transition of a GDR-state in class 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 to a GDR-state in class 
\begin_inset Formula $(M+1)$
\end_inset

. In such a transition the GDR is not affected and is just a "spectator". This is again a consequence of the two-body nature of the residual interaction. The subclasses 1, 2, 3 differ only in the angular momenta of the non-collective states the GDR is built on. Since a transition among these states must not change the angular momentum this part is diagonal in the subclass indices, i. e. 
\begin_inset Formula $(\Pi^{-1})_{Mm,(M+1)m}\not=0$
\end_inset

, only. Thus, these matrix elements are given by 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
(\Pi^{-1})_{Mm,(M+1)m}=2\pi\rho_{Mm}v_{n.c.}^{2}2\pi\rho_{Mm\rightarrow(M+1)m}^{acc},\end{equation}
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{Mm}^{J}(E)$
\end_inset

, m=1,2,3, is the exciton level densit
\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

p-h level densities
\end_layout

\end_inset

y 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{M-1}^{(J^{\prime},-\pi)}(E-E_{GDR})$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $J^{\prime}=(J-1),J,(J+1)$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{Mm\rightarrow(M+1)m}^{acc}(E)$
\end_inset

, m=1, 2, 3 are the accessible state densities 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{(M-1),J\rightarrow M,J^{\prime}}^{acc}(E-E_{GDR})$
