\begin_layout Standard

The calculation flow in the DDHMS model can be summarized in terms of the following steps:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

draw collision partner for the incoming nucleon (2p-1h state created) 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

draw energy (
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon$
\end_inset

) of the scattered nucleon (if bound go to step 5) 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

draw scattering angles for both particles 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

decide whether the scattered nucleon will be emitted, re-scattered or trapped
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate

if emitted appropriate cross section is augmented 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

if re-scatters additional particle-hole is created and we return to step 2 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

if trapped, go to step 5 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate

draw excitation energy of a particle in the remaining 1p-1h configuration (between 0
\begin_inset Formula $\div(U-\varepsilon)$
\end_inset

), if unbound go to step 3, if bound choose another existing 1p-1h pair and repeat step 5. 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

All excitons (including holes) are treated on equal footing and each of them is given a chance to interact or being emitted with 
\emph on
a priori
\emph default
 equal probability. The cascade ends when all excitons are bound. Below, we summarize various probability distributions which are used in concert with a random number generator.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

For choosing a collision partner it is assumed that the unlike interaction is 3 times more probable than the like one (
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{np}=3\sigma_{nn}$
\end_inset

). Thus, for the incident neutron we have 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{nn}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{np}$
\end_inset

 for the probability of exciting neutron and proton respectively
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
P_{nn}=\frac{(A-Z)}{(A-Z)+3Z},\label{Pnn}\end{equation}
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
P_{np}=1-P_{nn}\label{Pnp}\end{equation}
\end_inset

 and similarly for the incident proton
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
P_{pp}=\frac{Z}{Z+3(A-Z)},\label{Ppp}\end{equation}
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
P_{pn}=1-P_{pp}.\label{Ppn}\end{equation}
\end_inset

 The energy distribution of the scattered particles 
\begin_inset Formula $P(\varepsilon)$
\end_inset

 is given by the ratio of the 
\begin_inset Formula $(n-1)-$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-exciton level densities
\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

p-h level densities
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{n}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
P(\varepsilon)d\varepsilon=\frac{\rho_{n-1}(E-\varepsilon)g}{\rho_{n}(E)}d\varepsilon,\label{Penergy}\end{equation}
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $n=2\, or\,3$
\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\rho_{2}(E)=\frac{g(gV)}{2}\,\,\, if\,\,\, E>V,\label{ro2u}\end{equation}
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\rho_{2}(E)=\frac{g(gE)}{2}\,\,\, if\,\,\, E\leq V,\label{ro2d}\end{equation}
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\rho_{3}(E)=\frac{g^{3}\left[V(2E-V)\right]}{4}\,\,\, if\,\,\, E\geq V.\label{ro3}\end{equation}
\end_inset

 Here, 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 is a potential well depth. The emission probability is calculated as
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
P_{\nu}(\varepsilon-Q)=\frac{\lambda_{c}(\varepsilon-Q)}{\lambda_{c}(\varepsilon-Q)+\lambda_{+}(\varepsilon)},\label{Pnu}\end{equation}
\end_inset

 with the emission rate being
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\lambda_{c}(\varepsilon-Q)\sim\frac{\sigma_{\nu}(\varepsilon-Q)(\varepsilon-Q)(2S+1)\mu_{\nu}}{g}.\label{lambdac}\end{equation}
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{\nu}$
\end_inset

 is an inverse reaction cross section, 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 is a binding energy, 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 is a single particle density, 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 denotes nucleon spin, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{\nu}$
\end_inset

 stands for the reduced nucleon mass. Following the hybrid
\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

HYBRID
\end_layout

\end_inset

 model, 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{+}(\varepsilon)$
\end_inset

 is calculated from the mean free path of a nucleon in nuclear matter.
\end_layout

