\begin_layout Standard

The statistical model used in the EMPIRE is an advanced implementation of the Hauser-Feshbach
\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Hauser-Feshbach
\end_layout

\end_inset

 theory. The exact angular momentum and parity coupling is observed. The emission of neutrons, protons, 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

-particles, and a light ion is taken into account along with the competing fission channel. The full 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

-cascade in the residual nuclei is considered. Particular attention is dedicated to the determination of the level densities
\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

level densities
\end_layout

\end_inset

, which can be calculated in the non-adiabatic approach allowing for the rotational and vibrational enhancements. These collective effects are gradually removed above a certain energy. Level densities acquire dynamic features through the dependence of the rotational enhancement on the shape of a nucleus.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

In the frame of the statistical model of nuclear reactions the contribution of the Compound Nucleus (CN) state 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 with spin 
\begin_inset Formula $J$
\end_inset

, parity 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

, and excitation energy 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 to a channel 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 is given by the ratio of the channel width 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma_{b}$
\end_inset

 to the total width 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma_{tot}=\sum_{c}\Gamma_{c}$
\end_inset

 multiplied by the population of this state 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{a}(E,J,\pi)$
\end_inset

. This also holds for secondary CNs that are formed due to subsequent emissions of particles. The only difference is that while the first CN is initially excited to the unique (incident channel compatible) energy, the secondary CNs are created with excitation energies which spread over the available energy interval. Each such state contributes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\sigma_{b}(E,J,\pi)=\sigma_{a}(E,J,\pi)\frac{\Gamma_{b}(E,J,\pi)}{\sum_{c}\Gamma_{c}(E,J,\pi)}\label{Hauser}\end{equation}
\end_inset

 to the cross section. These have to be summed over spin 
\begin_inset Formula $J$
\end_inset

 and parity 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

, and integrated over excitation energy 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 (in case of daughter CN) to obtain observable cross sections. The particle decay width is given by
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\Gamma_{c}(E,J,\pi)=\frac{1}{2\pi\rho_{CN}(E,J,\pi)}\sum_{J'=0}^{\infty}\sum_{\pi'}\sum_{j=J'-J}^{J+J'}\int_{0}^{E-B_{c}}\rho_{c}(E',J',\pi')T_{c}^{l,j}(E-B_{c}-E')dE',\label{pwidth}\end{equation}
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent

where 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{c}$
\end_inset

 is the binding energy of particle 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 in the compound nucleus, 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 is the level density
\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

level density
\end_layout

\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{c}^{l,j}(\epsilon)$
\end_inset

 stands for the transmission coefficient for particle 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 having channel energy 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon=E-B_{c}-E'$
\end_inset

 and orbital angular momentum 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

, which together with the particle spin 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 couples to the channel angular momentum 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

. For the discrete levels (characterized by the energy 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{i}$
\end_inset

, spin 
\begin_inset Formula $J_{i}$
\end_inset

, and parity 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{i}$
\end_inset

) the level density 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho(E,J',\pi')$
\end_inset

 reduces to 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta(E-E_{i})\delta_{(J',J_{i})}\delta_{(\pi',\pi_{i})}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

The fission width reads 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\Gamma_{f}(E,J,\pi)=\frac{1}{2\pi\rho_{CN}(E,J,\pi)}\int_{0}^{E-E_{sad}(J)}\rho_{f}(\epsilon,J,\pi)T_{f}^{HW}(E-E_{sad}(J)-\epsilon)d\epsilon,\label{fwidth}\end{equation}
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent

where 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{sad}(J)$
\end_inset

 is the energy of the saddle point with angular momentum 
\begin_inset Formula $J$
\end_inset

. The parity selection rules are implicit in Eqs. 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pwidth"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fwidth"

\end_inset

. The energy of the saddle point is given by the sum of the fission barrier 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{f}(J)$
\end_inset

 and the rotational energy of the nucleus at spin 
\begin_inset Formula $J$
\end_inset

. Since nuclei at the saddle point are known to have a strong prolate deformation, with the angular momentum vector perpendicular to the symmetry axis, the rotational energy contribution to the saddle point energy is given by
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\frac{\hbar^{2}J(J+1)}{2(\Im_{\bot})_{sad}}.\label{Erot}\end{equation}
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent

Here 
\begin_inset Formula $\Im_{\bot}$
\end_inset

 is a moment of inertia perpendicular to the symmetry axis calculated by the BARMOM
\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

BARMOM
\end_layout

\end_inset

 routine 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after ""
key "sierk"

\end_inset

. In the Hill-Wheeler 
\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Hill-Wheeler
\end_layout

\end_inset

 approximation the fission transmission coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{f}^{HW}$
\end_inset

 is given by
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
T_{f}^{HW}(E-E_{sad}(J)-\epsilon)=\frac{1}{1+exp[-\frac{2\pi}{\hbar\omega}(E-E_{sad}(J)-\epsilon)]}\,.\label{THW}\end{equation}
\end_inset

 By default, 
\begin_inset Formula $\hbar\omega=1$
\end_inset

 MeV is taken. This formulation is adequate for heavy ion induced reactions but needs refinement in the case of fission induced by low energy nucleons. This shortcoming will be removed in the later versions of the code.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection

Level densities
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

EMPIRE accounts for various models describing level densities
\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

level densities
\end_layout

\end_inset

 and includes several respective parameterizations. In each case equal parity distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho(E,J,\pi)=\frac{1}{2}\rho(E,J)$
\end_inset

 is assumed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

Choice of the proper representation depends on a case being considered. For the nucleon induced reactions, with CN excited up to about 20 MeV, the Gilbert-Cameron approach is recommended. It assures the most accurate description of level densities in the energy range up to the neutron binding energy. The collective effects are included in the level density parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

, providing reasonable estimate of the level densities as long as damping of the collective effects is irrelevant. The relatively low angular momentum introduced by the incident projectile justifies neglect of dynamical effects. However, these effects have to be taken into account in case of the heavy ion induced reactions and/or higher excitation energies. In these cases, the dynamic approach which accounts for the shape-dependent collective enhancements, their damping with increasing energy, and the temperature dependence of the 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

-parameter should be adopted.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

Gilbert-Cameron approach
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

The Gilbert-Cameron approach 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after ""
key "gc"

\end_inset

 splits excitation energy in two regions. Different functional forms of level densities
\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

level densities
\end_layout

\end_inset

 are applied in each of them. At low excitation energies (below the matching point 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{x}$
\end_inset

) the constant temperature formula is used
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\rho_{T}(E)=\frac{1}{T}exp\left[(E-\Delta-E_{0})/T\right],\label{lgcld}\end{equation}
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 is the nuclear temperature, 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 is the excitation energy (
\begin_inset Formula $E=U+\Delta$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta$
\end_inset

 being the pairing correction), and 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{0}$
\end_inset

 is an adjustable energy shift. Above 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{x}$
\end_inset

 the Fermi gas formula is applied
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\rho_{F}(U)=\frac{exp(2\sqrt{aU})}{12\sqrt{2}\sigma(U)a^{1/4}U^{5/4}}.\label{ferld}\end{equation}
\end_inset

 The level density parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 is assumed to be energy independent. The spin cut-off factor 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma(U)$
\end_inset

 is given by
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\sigma^{2}(U)=0.146A^{2/3}\sqrt{aU}.\label{sigld}\end{equation}
\end_inset

 Three model parameters, 
\begin_inset Formula $T,\, U_{x},$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{0}$
\end_inset

, are determined by the requirement that the level density and its derivative are continuous at the matching point 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{x}$
\end_inset

, and by fitting cumulative number of discrete levels with the integral of Eq. 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "lgcld"

\end_inset

. The first of the conditions implies
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\frac{1}{T}=\sqrt{a/U_{x}}-\frac{3}{2U_{x}}.\label{condUT}\end{equation}
\end_inset

 The code will not(!) stop if the discrete level scheme is incompatible with the level densit
\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

