\begin_layout Section

Width fluctuation correction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

The Hauser-Feshbach
\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Hauser-Feshbach
\end_layout

\end_inset

 model assumes that there are no correlations among various reaction channels contributing to the formation and decay of a certain compound nucleus state J
\begin_inset Formula $^{\pi}$
\end_inset

. An obvious case for which this assumption breaks down is the elastic channel, for which entrance and exit channels are the same. This correlation leads to an increase of the elastic channel cross section compared to the Hauser-Feshbach predictions. At higher incident energies, at which the elastic channel is one among many inelastic ones, this increase can be safely neglected. However, if there are only a few open channels the increase of the elastic channels turns out to have serious consequences on other channels (particularly on inelastic scattering and capture).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

One of the models which allows these effects to be taken into account has been proposed by Hofmann, Richert, Tepel and Weidenmueller 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after ""
key "HRTW"

\end_inset

 (HRTW). In the case of no direct reaction contribution, the averaged 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

-matrix element connecting channels 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 can be written as
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
<S>_{ab}=\delta_{ab}e^{i\varsigma_{ab}}(1-T_{a})^{1/2},\label{Sab}\end{equation}
\end_inset

 where
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
T_{a}=1-|<S>_{aa}|^{2}\label{Ta}\end{equation}
\end_inset

 is an optical model transmission coefficient. The HRTW model assumes that the Compound Nucleus (CN) cross sections 
\series bold
factorize
\series default
 and can be expressed through a product of the channel dependent quantities 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi$
\end_inset

. This would be the famous Bohr's assumption if not for the elastic enhancement factor 
\begin_inset Formula $W_{a}$
\end_inset

, which has been introduced by HRTW in order to account for the elastic channel correlation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
<\sigma_{ab}^{fl}>=\xi_{a}\xi_{b}\quad a\neq b\qquad and\qquad<\sigma_{a}^{fl}>=W_{a}\xi_{a}^{2}.\label{Sig-fluc}\end{equation}
\end_inset

 Setting
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\xi_{a}=\frac{V_{a}}{\sqrt{\sum_{c}V_{c}}}\label{ksi}\end{equation}
\end_inset

 we get for the CN cross section
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\sigma_{ab}^{CN}\equiv<\sigma_{ab}^{fl}>=V_{a}V_{b}\left(\sum_{c}V_{c}\right)^{-1}\left[1+\delta_{ab}\left(W_{a}-1\right)\right].\label{Sig-flucV}\end{equation}
\end_inset

 Taking into account that the incoming flux has to be conserved (unitarity condition) we find the relation between 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

s, the elastic enhancement factor (
\begin_inset Formula $W_{a}$
\end_inset

), and the transmission coefficient (
\begin_inset Formula $T_{a}$
\end_inset

) 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
V_{a}=T_{a}\left[1+\frac{V_{a}}{\left(\sum_{c}V_{c}\right)}\left(W_{a}-1\right)\right]^{-1}.\label{Va}\end{equation}
\end_inset

 This equation can be solved for 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{a}$
\end_inset

 by iteration once all 
\begin_inset Formula $W_{a}$
\end_inset

 are known. The current version of EMPIRE uses 
\begin_inset Formula $W_{a}$
\end_inset

 derived from the analysis of numerically generated sets of 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

-matrices
\begin_inset space ~

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after ""
key "HHM"

\end_inset

. This exercises was tailored to the cases that include many weak channels coupled to a few strong channels, which is typical of neutron capture reactions. The resulting formula for the elastic enhancement factor is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
W_{a}=1+2\left[1+T_{a}^{F}\right]^{-1}+87\left(\frac{T_{a}-T_{ave}}{\sum_{c}T_{c}}\right)^{2}\left(\frac{T_{a}}{\sum_{c}T_{c}}\right)^{5},\label{Wa}\end{equation}
\end_inset

 with
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
F=4\frac{T_{ave}}{\sum_{c}T_{c}}\left(1+\frac{T_{a}}{\sum_{c}T_{c}}\right)\left(1+3\frac{T_{ave}}{\sum_{c}T_{c}}\right)^{-1},\label{Wa-F}\end{equation}
\end_inset

 which completes formulation of the model.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

The widths fluctuation correction has been added by Herman to improve code performance at low incident energies. The theory requires that each 
\begin_inset Formula $J^{\pi}$
\end_inset

 state in the highest energy bin of the first CN is treated separately. In order to define physical elastic channels the fusion cross section to a given 
\begin_inset Formula $J^{\pi}$
\end_inset

 capture state is decomposed into 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

 components (actual version of EMPIRE uses 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{l}$
\end_inset

 rather than 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{lj}$
\end_inset

). In the first sweep 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{l}$
\end_inset

s for all channels are stored and elastic channels recorded. In the second sweep 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{l}$
\end_inset

 and HF-type
\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Hauser-Feshbach
\end_layout

\end_inset

 denominator are calculated, and the enhancement is applied to the elastic channels. Finally, the third sweep is needed to normalize partial widths and calculate cross sections. For practical reasons, the channels are divided into strong (
\begin_inset Formula $T_{l}\geq0.0001$
\end_inset

) and week ones (
\begin_inset Formula $T_{l}<0.0001$
\end_inset

). The effective transmission coefficients (
\begin_inset Formula $V_{a}$
\end_inset

) for the strong channels are calculated by iteration until the requested accuracy is achieved, while only one iteration is applied to obtain 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{a}$
\end_inset

 for the weak channels. Particle channels are treated explicitly while 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

-channels are lumped into one or more fictitious channels. By default, the HRTW model is applied below 5 MeV incident energy. Users have the option to apply it at all energies or to turn it off.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section

Photoabsorption
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

A model of photonuclear reactions must account for the different reaction mechanisms involved in the initial photonuclear excitation process and the subsequent decay of the excited nucleus by particle and gamma-ray emission. At low energies, below about 30 MeV, the Giant Dipole Resonance (GDR) is the dominant excitation mechanism, where a collective bulk oscillation of the neutrons against the protons occurs. At higher energies, up to approximately 150 MeV, photoabsorption on a neutron-proton pair (a quasi-deuteron, QD), which has a large dipole moment, is the dominant mechanism.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

In EMPIRE, the photoabsorption cross section is calculated as the sum of two components
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after ""
key "PHNuc"

\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\sigma_{abs}(E_{\gamma})=\sigma_{GDR}(E_{\gamma})+\sigma_{QD}(E_{\gamma}).\]
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

The GDR component, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{GDR}(E_{\gamma})$
\end_inset

, is given by a Lorentzian shape, with parameters describing the total absorption of the giant dipole resonance. The expression used is given in detail in 2.9.5, but takes the basic form
\begin_inset Formula \[
\sigma_{GDR}(E_{\gamma})=\sum_{i}\sigma_{i}\frac{(E_{\gamma}\Gamma_{i})^{2}}{(E_{\gamma}^{2}-E_{i}^{2})^{2}+(E_{\gamma}\Gamma_{i})^{2}}\,,\]
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{i}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma_{i}$
\end_inset

 are the GDR peak cross section, energy and width, respectively. The summation is limited to 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1$
\end_inset

 for spherical nuclei, while for deformed nuclei the resonance is split and one uses 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1,2$
\end_inset

. As a rule, the parameters are derived from fits to experimental data or from systematics
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after ""
key "RIPL2"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

The QD component, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{QD}(E_{\gamma})$
\end_inset

, is taken from the model of Chadwick 
\emph on
et al.
\emph default
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after ""
key "chadQD"

\end_inset

, which uses a Levinger-type theory. It relates the nuclear photoabsorption cross section to the experimental deuteron photodisintegration cross section, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{d}(E_{\gamma})$
\end_inset

, as
\begin_inset Formula \[
\sigma_{QD}(E_{\gamma})=L\frac{NZ}{A}\sigma_{d}(E_{\gamma})\, f(E_{\gamma})\,.\]
\end_inset

 Here, the Levinger parameter was derived as 
\begin_inset Formula $L=6.5$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f(E_{\gamma})$
\end_inset

 is the Pauli-blocking function, which reduces the free deuteron cross section 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{d}(E_{\gamma})$
\end_inset

 to account for Pauli blocking of the excited neutron and proton by the nuclear medium. The experimental deuteron photodisintegration cross section was parametrized as 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\sigma_{d}(E_{\gamma})=61.2\frac{(E_{\gamma}-2.24)^{3/2}}{E_{\gamma}^{3}}\,,\]
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{\gamma}$
\end_inset

 in MeV and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{d}$
\end_inset

 in mb. The Pauli-blocking function was found by Chadwick 
\emph on
et al.
\emph default
 to be a multidimensional integral whose solution could be well approximated in the energy range 20 -- 140 MeV by the polynomial expression
\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray*}
f(E_{\gamma}) & = & \;8.3714\times10^{-2}-9.8343\times10^{-3}E_{\gamma}+4.1222\times10^{-4}E_{\gamma}^{2}\\
 &  & -3.4762\times10^{-6}E_{\gamma}^{3}+9.3537\times10^{-9}E_{\gamma}^{4}\,,\end{eqnarray*}
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{\gamma}$
\end_inset

 in MeV. In Ref. 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after ""
key "chadQD"

\end_inset

, the Pauli-blocking function was not parametrized below 20 MeV, where it tends to zero, or above 140 MeV, where it tends to unity. As the contribution needs to be defined at all energies considered, EMPIRE follows the example of Ref. 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after ""
key "PHNuc"

\end_inset

 and uses an exponential shape, 
\begin_inset Formula $f(E_{\gamma})=\exp(-D/E_{\gamma})$
\end_inset

, for energies below 20 MeV and above 140 MeV, with 
\begin_inset Formula $D=73.3$
\end_inset

 MeV for 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{\gamma}<20$
\end_inset

 MeV and 
\begin_inset Formula $D=24.2$
\end_inset

 MeV for 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{\gamma}>140$
\end_inset

 MeV. This form has the correct behavior in that it tends to zero at 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{\gamma}=0$
\end_inset

 and to unity for large 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{\gamma}$
\end_inset

, and is continuous with the previous equation at 20 and 140 MeV.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

Preequilibrium reaction mechanisms become important for incident photon energies above 10 to 15 MeV. In the photoabsorption mechanisms described above, the initial nuclear excitation can be understood in terms of particle-hole excitations (
\begin_inset Formula $1p1h$
\end_inset

 for the GDR; 
\begin_inset Formula $2p2h$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $2p1h$
\end_inset

 for QD processes) and thus it is natural to use a preequilibrium theory of particle-hole processes to describe the preequilibrium emission and damping to equilibrium during the evolution of the reaction. Such models can be used to calculate photonuclear reactions for incident photons with energies up to about 140 MeV, which is the threshold for pion production. At present, EMPIRE permits the calculation of preequilibrium emission in photonuclear reactions using either the exciton model module PCROSS
\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

PCROSS
\end_layout

\end_inset

 or the Hybrid Monte-Carlo Simulation module HMS
\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

HMS
\end_layout

\end_inset

. Both implementations of photoabsorption represent the GDR fraction as an initial 
\begin_inset Formula $1p1h$
\end_inset

 excitation and the QD fraction as an initial 
\begin_inset Formula $2p2h$
\end_inset

 excitation. The implementation of photoabsorption in PCROSS does not take into account the correlation of the two holes created through the QD mechanism, which would require an initial configuration closer to a 
\begin_inset Formula $2p1h$
\end_inset

 one than to a 
\begin_inset Formula $2p2h$
\end_inset

 one
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after ""
key "PHNuc"

\end_inset

. The implementation in HMS takes this correlation into account in a manner consistent with the model of Ref. 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after ""
key "chadQD"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

Following the possible emission of preequilibrium particles, the remaining nuclear system reaches equilibrium, after which it decays by sequential particle or gamma-ray emission (or possibly fission) until the nuclear ground state is reached. In EMPIRE, the Hauser-Feshbach theory is used to calculate cross sections for these processes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

Much more information on photonuclear reactions can be found in Ref. 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
