. In the simplest version of the model (FISOPT=0), the transmission coefficients through the humps (
\begin_inset Formula $T_{A}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{B}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{C}$
\end_inset

) of a barrier corresponding to a particular discrete transition state, are calculated with Hill-Wheeler formula
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
T_{ij}(EKJ\pi)=\frac{1}{1+\exp\{-(2\pi/\hbar\omega_{i})[E-E_{i}]\}}\quad i=A,B,C.\label{thw}\end{equation}
\end_inset

 The total transmission coefficient through a hump is sum of two contributions corresponding to the discrete and continuous part of the transition state spectrum
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
T_{i}(EJ\pi)=\sum_{K\leq J}T_{i}(EKJ\pi)+\int_{E_{ci}}^{\infty}\frac{\rho_{i}(\varepsilon J\pi)d\varepsilon}{{1+\exp\left[-\frac{2\pi}{\hbar\omega_{i}}(E-V_{i}-\varepsilon)\right]}\quad i}=A,B\label{tjt}\end{equation}
\end_inset

 Increasing the excitation energy, the strength of the imaginary potential increases and the entire flux transmitted through the inner hump is absorbed in the second (isomeric) well (
\begin_inset Formula $T_{abs}\rightarrow T_{A}$
\end_inset

), and the direct transmission through the entire barrier disappears (
\begin_inset Formula $T_{dir}\rightarrow0$
\end_inset

). Therefore, the direct fission occurs only for sub-barrier excitation energies and occurs only through discrete channels
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
T_{dir}(EJ\pi)=\sum_{K\leq J}T_{dir}(EKJ\pi),\label{tdirt}\end{equation}
\end_inset

 while the absorption in the isomeric well occurs through all fission channels. In full 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

-mixing approximation all the discrete channels with the same 
\begin_inset Formula $J\pi$
\end_inset

 contribute irrespective of their 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 value to the total absorption coefficient. The continuum fission channels contribute at higher energies, where the class II states are completely damped and the entire flux transmitted through the inner barrier is absorbed in the isomeric
