For the sake of clarity, we start by describing the `script-driven' mode of EMPIRE:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

EMPIRE execution most commonly involves the following four operation sequences, which are described in more detail below:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

"runE" sequence prepares data, runs the main calculation and prepares ZVView plots of pre-defined cross sections.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

"format" sequence generates the ENDF formatted file.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

"verify" sequence checks the ENDF file for formal correctness and internal consistency. 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

"process" sequence performs post-processing to prepare a derived ENDF file, from which more advanced plotting is done. 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

This complete sequence is intended for the production of evaluated files in ENDF-6 format, but for theoretical modeling, the "runE" script is likely sufficient. However, in this case automatic plotting is limited to the cross sections. A more detailed description of the task sequences is described below. 
