\begin_layout Section

ENDF formatting
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

The ENDF formatted file is created by the user selecting the ENDF option in the input file (*.
\emph on
inp
\emph default
). This instructs EMPIRE to write all necessary information to the output file 
\emph on
*.out
\emph default
, which may actually become very long, depending to some extent on the choice of input options in the EMPIRE calculations. This file is processed by the utility code EMPEND
\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

EMPEND
\end_layout

\end_inset

 written by Trkov, which creates the ENDF-6 formatted file.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

Rather than providing exclusive cross sections and associated spectra for each of the reactions separately, EMPIRE can output inclusive cross sections, spectra and double-differential cross sections. This means that the total emission spectra of neutrons, protons, 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

-particles and 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

s are printed, instead of individual contributions from the reactions, with the exception of some distinct reactions that are always treated exclusively (e.g. inelastic, (n,2n), (n,p), etc.) This is the preferred mode of EMPIRE execution when ENDF formatting is required. EMPEND
\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

EMPEND
\end_layout

\end_inset

 automatically recognizes the calculation options from the contents and acts accordingly.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

EMPIRE also calculates cross sections for the production of metastable isomers. EMPEND recognizes these and stores them in ENDF File
\begin_inset space ~

\end_inset

10. Cross sections for radionuclide production, which can not be uniquely associated with any specific reaction (i.e. an ENDF MT number) are lumped into File
\begin_inset space ~

\end_inset

3 MT
\begin_inset space ~

\end_inset

5, but to preserve the complete information, the radionuclide production is stored in File
\begin_inset space ~

\end_inset

10, MT
\begin_inset space ~

\end_inset

5. This can be done because according to ENDF-6 rules the cross sections in File
\begin_inset space ~

\end_inset

10 by definition are not required for the reconstruction of redundant reactions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

The ENDF file has to obey the rules of sorting the data in increasing order by data type (MF number) and reaction type (MT number), so several sweeps of the EMPIRE output file must be made, which may slow down the formatting process considerably. In general, the required operations are described as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

In the first sweep the cross sections and the corresponding reaction Q-values are extracted. All reading is done with the REAMF3 routine. 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

In the next sweep all reactions for which particle spectra are given are identified. All reading is done with the SCNMF6 routine. 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

Another sweep is made for each reaction having angular distributions. This applies to the elastic and all discrete level reactions (inelastic neutron, alpha and proton emission). 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

Next follows a sweep for each reaction having energy-angle correlated outgoing particle distributions. 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

Finally, a sweep is made for the remaining reactions, particularly the (n,
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

) reaction, for which the particle distributions are coded in ENDF File-6. 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

In the first sweep radionuclide production cross sections are located and the MT numbers are assigned, when possible. Cross sections, which can not be identified uniquely by an MT number are assigned MT=10(Z*1000+A)+LFS where LFS is the final isomeric state of the nuclide. The spin of the target nucleus, the S
\begin_inset Formula $_0$
\end_inset

-strength function, the average gamma width, the average level spacing and the energy-dependent scattering radius are also extracted to enable the assembly of the dummy resonance parameter file.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

In the second sweep, all reactions that do not have explicitly given spectra are identified. When many exclusive spectra are requested in the EMPIRE calculation, there may be cases where particle spectra are given but no MT number is assigned. The spectra are ignored, the cross sections are added to MT=5 and particle production cross sections for this MT are incremented. This preserves particle multiplicities, but spectral shapes may become distorted. After the second sweep, all necessary information is available to write the comments-section (MF=1) and the prompt nu-bar (if the nuclide is fissile). For incident neutrons a dummy resonance file (File
\begin_inset space ~

\end_inset

2) is constructed. The cross section data found on the file are fitted by a cubic spline and entered into the output ENDF file on a user-defined dense energy grid, thinned to the specified tolerance and taking reaction thresholds into account. If desired, the spline interpolation may be suppressed and the energy points found on the file are entered directly into the ENDF formatted file. The angular distributions for discrete level reactions that appear in the ENDF File
\begin_inset space ~

\end_inset

4 sections are extracted from the spectra on the EMPIRE output file, interpolated to the appropriate energy, if necessary. Legendre polynomial coefficients in the centre-of-mass are fitted to the distributions. For elastic scattering the Legendre coefficients are copied directly from the EMPIRE output; If more than 64 Legendre coefficients are required, formatting switches automatically to pointwise representation. The correlated energy-angle distributions for continuum reactions that appear in ENDF File-6 sections are entered in Legendre polynomial representation in the centre-of- mass coordinate system. The maximum Legendre order is limited to 64. For reactions with relatively smooth angular distributions, the number of coefficients is reduced accordingly. Photon production information for discrete levels can be stored in ENDF Files
\begin_inset space ~

\end_inset

12 and 14. The spectra for the continuum are included in File-6 (rather than File
\begin_inset space ~

\end_inset

15). File
\begin_inset space ~

\end_inset

12 contains photon transition probabilities and photon emission probabilities for discrete level reactions, while File
\begin_inset space ~

\end_inset

14 contains the corresponding angular distributions, which are assumed isotropic. The gamma spectra of the (n,gamma) reaction are presently stored in File-6. Primary gammas, which are optionally printed in the Empire output explicitly are not formatted. This option should not be used when ENDF formatting is required. By default, primary gammas are included in the photon spectrum in tabular form. 
\end_layout

