\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000

QFIS Liquid drop fission barrier multiplier. QFIS>1 decreases fission channel. 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling

SHRJ Shell correction to fission barrier is damped to 1/2 (Eq. 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "BfJfade"

\end_inset

) at the spin defined by SHRJ. For negative shell corrections, lowering SHRJ will increase the fission channel, at least at sufficiently high incident energies. Opposite is true for positive shell corrections. 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling

SHRD Diffuseness of the shell correction damping (Eq. 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "BfJfade"

\end_inset

). The size and sign of the effect depend on the actual spin population of the fissioning nucleus. 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling

TEMP0 Temperature at which temperature-damping of the shell correction (Eq. 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "BfTfade"

\end_inset

) starts to be effective. Increasing (decreasing) this value will decrease (increase) fission above the temperature defined as min(TEMP0, 1.65) (1.65 is the default value) and will have no effect on the fission cross sections at incident energies corresponding to lower temperatures. 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling

SHRT Multiplier in the exponent of the temperature-damping of the shell correction (Eq. 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "BfTfade"

\end_inset

). Increasing this parameter will increase fission above the temperature selected with TEMP0 (no change below). 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling

DEFGA Amplitude of the Gaussian term defined by Eq. 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "BfJfade"

\end_inset

. Setting to a positive value will increase fission barrier and therefore decrease fission channel, but only if the states with spins within the range defined below by DEFGW and DEFGP are populated. On the contrary, a negative value will increase the fission cross section. The Gaussian term is used to simulate irregularities in the shell correction related to the incidental bunching or de-bunching of single particle levels due to the rotation-induced change in nuclear deformation. Generally, the effect will only be observed in the limited range of incident energies. 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling

DEFGW 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta J_{G}$
\end_inset

 (width in spin) in the Gaussian (term of Eq. 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "BfJfade"

\end_inset

). Increasing DEFGW will magnify the effect described above and enlarge the range of incident energies being affected. 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling

DEFGP 
\begin_inset Formula $J_{G}$
\end_inset

 (spin position) of the Gaussian (term Eq. 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "BfJfade"

\end_inset

). The value of DEFGP defines the mean value of the incident energy range affected by the Gaussian term, which increases with DEFGP. Setting this parameter above the maximum spin for nucleus stability reduces or even eliminates the effect. 
